// A boxed record whose layout walk reaches a SECOND, pointer-backed cycle.
//
// `A` and `B` close a cycle entirely by value, so both are boxed: every value of them is
// a pointer, and `repr_shape` computes the pointee layout. `L` closes a different cycle
// through a `List`, which needs no box — the list pointer already makes it finite.
//
// `repr_shape` passed an EMPTY cut set to that layout walk, on the reasoning that boxing
// already cuts every record cycle. It does — but only record cycles. Laying `A` out
// inline descends through `l: L` into `List[L]` and back into `L`, a cycle boxing does
// not cut and an empty cut set does not cut either, so the compiler recursed forever and
// died with a stack overflow instead of compiling.
//
// Each half alone is fine — `L` on its own compiles, and `A`/`B` on their own compile —
// so it is the two together that has no terminating walk, which is why neither existing
// recursive-record test catches it. Building the values is enough to trigger it: the
// crash was in laying the types out, not in any operation on them.

use std::io;

record L {
    xs: List[L],
}

record B {
    a: A | null,
}

record A {
    b: B,
    l: L,
}

fn main() {
    let leaf = L { xs: [] };
    let a = A { b: B { a: null }, l: leaf };
    io::println("laid out");
}
